yday life was composed, tracing both the intimate and the mass changes that the people endured. Using novel perspectives and methods, chapters range across the experiences of work, art and death, the way Scots conceived of themselves and their homes, and the way the 'old Scotland' of oppressive community rules broke down from mid-century as the country reinvented its everyday life and culture.This volume brings together leading cultural historians of twentieth-century Scotland to study the apparently mundane activities of people's lives, traversing the key spaces where daily experience is composed to expose the controversial personal and national politics that ritual and practice can generate.Key features:Contains an overview of the material changes experienced by Scots in their everyday lives during the course of the centuryFocuses on some of the key areas of change in everyday experience, from the way Scots spent their Sundays to the homes in which they lived, from the work they undertook to the culture they consumed and eventually the way they diedPays particular attention to identity as well as experience"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aScottish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aAbrams, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartie, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Callum G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Callum, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFleming, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoyster, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJamieson, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcFarland, E. W., econtributor.4ctb4http